newsitem.title: USA: CME Sep lumber ends limit up at new high, cash up.
newsitem.headline: CME Sep lumber ends limit up at new high, cash up.

text.p: CME September lumber futures ended up the $10.00-per-thousand-board-feet daily limit at a new contract high of $396.50 per tbf as another round of cash lumber price increases sparked commercial buying, traders said.
Other months finished $9.20 to $5.40 higher with November up $9.20 at $359.70 per tbf.
"There is not enough wood out there. People are snapping it up," said Roger Champagne, cash dealer for Capital Forest Products Inc in Annapolis, Md.
Cash spruce was quoted in the $417 to $420 area Thursday, versus cash quotes Wednesday of $412, sources said.
Trading in spruce slowed Wednesday and was quiet at the start Thursday but demand grew and cash prices started to rise again, cash sources said.
"Demand far exceeds supply right now," Champagne said.
Prudential Securities, Refco, Merrill Lynch and locals bought. Saul Stone bought November and sold September on the rally, pit sources said.
